@Jake

Your comment alters what was said. The puzzle being hard or not was not the issue. I think D expressed it perfectly clearly. It was the way in which it was made difficult that D took issue with. So do I.

Without the tedium of listing examples, I too found much of the cluing highly questionable. It's just my opinion. I don't have to defend it before a panel of experts.

@D

If it feels like I’m always defending puzzles, it’s because if I enjoy them (and usually I do) I’d hate to see them go away because some proportion of people don’t like them so I want to be sure my voice gets heard. If you think the clueing could be better etc. then that’s different but if you think the theme is too hard then that’s where I’d want to speak up because I liked it and I’d hate to see themes of this type go away (respecting of course your opinion to feel and say otherwise).
Regarding Googling things to put in the puzzle to make them harder, I doubt this is happening, at least on theme puzzles. When I create puzzles what happens is I end up having some difficult entries that are necessary for the constraints of the theme entries. Yes, a program may identify those and yes sometimes I need to Google them because I don’t know them. Then I have to decide if I can get away with it, try to make sure the crossing clues are fair, check to see if the word has been used before, etc. When I assess a puzzle’s value, part of my assessment is whether the clunky areas are justified because of a difficult but entertaining theme. In any case I guarantee this constructor didn’t go out of their way to pick ETOILE or KIROV or TSENG, they were just stuck with them; maybe a better constructor could have done better but it wasn’t deliberate. Except maybe ZORK because DORK could have worked as well, but perhaps the constructor just had fond memories of the game.

